good person too. I'm very smart and, you know, I have a lot of great ideas and good things to offer.

00:40:13.959 --> 00:40:17.639
And, um, so just kind of keep that in mind as you're growing in your career.

00:40:19.560 --> 00:40:24.199
Yeah. Also, like, don't feel like you have to be the one responsible. Like, let's say,

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:30.280
uh, there is no diversity efforts and then you are going to be the one doing the whole work

00:40:30.280 --> 00:40:37.000
because, so like try to get other people to help you as well to have allies. And also the outside

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:43.639
network is very important on those times. So you don't feel lonely. So we have this support

00:40:43.639 --> 00:40:53.080
around you that keeps you going. Great. Um, so I mean, all of you had such different paths. Um,

00:40:53.080 --> 00:40:57.399
but we have a question here about for a young data scientist trying to get their first job,

00:40:57.399 --> 00:41:02.280
should they be looking at large companies or startups? Do you have any specific advice about

00:41:02.280 --> 00:41:13.959
what context might be the best place to start? So I came, so I always worked for startups until

00:41:13.959 --> 00:41:21.560
moving to IBM two years ago, almost two years ago. So I went from a company where we were 20 people

00:41:21.560 --> 00:41:30.840
to like 300,000. Uh, it's a big jump. I don't know what is better. I think if you are a beginner,

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:35.080
the best company is the company where you're going, again, you are going to have support

00:41:35.080 --> 00:41:43.080
mentorship because it's so hard to break into this, you know, career without having someone

00:41:43.080 --> 00:41:49.159
mentoring you. So if there is a startup that you have a good network and support, yeah, go for it.

00:41:49.719 --> 00:41:54.840
But if you have opportunity to work for a big company, you probably have more mentorship,

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:59.479
but also like you are going to be more specialized than a startup where you do,

00:41:59.479 --> 00:42:06.040
you have to do everything from getting the data, cleaning the data, data engineering to modeling

00:42:06.040 --> 00:42:12.120
and putting production, for example. Can I also just give a pitch for the idea of potentially

00:42:12.120 --> 00:42:17.399
considering consulting? Um, because I think it's a really good way that you can gain experience.

00:42:18.199 --> 00:42:22.120
And, um, you know, even if your ultimate goal is to become, say a data scientist,

00:42:22.120 --> 00:42:27.239
I think there are a lot of opportunities to use the types of skills that you have as an R user.

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:33.239
You know, outside of that, that title, um, in ways that can really be impactful for the

00:42:33.239 --> 00:42:40.040
organizations that you work for. I mean, just as a, as a minor example, um, one of the clients

00:42:40.040 --> 00:42:46.840
that I was training recently, um, was working, doing an evaluation of, um, an afterschool program

00:42:46.840 --> 00:42:49.800
and they were working at a hundred different schools and they had to produce literally a

00:42:49.800 --> 00:42:55.159
hundred reports. I taught them about parameterized reporting and it just like completely blew their

00:42:55.159 --> 00:42:58.919
mind. The idea that they could, you know, automate that and not have to manually produce

00:42:58.919 --> 00:43:03.800
a hundred reports. They're not a data science firm that, you know, that's not how they identify

00:43:03.800 --> 00:43:08.840
themselves, but those types of skills can, can be really useful and serve a wide variety of

00:43:08.840 --> 00:43:14.439
organizations. Um, and you can do that sometimes through consulting. I actually have a follow-up

00:43:14.439 --> 00:43:19.399
question directed to you, David, on that point, which is how did you get started consulting?

00:43:19.399 --> 00:43:22.600
How did you start out finding clients and how has that changed over time?

00:43:23.560 --> 00:43:29.320
Um, so I started out consulting, um, the honest answer is because I had twins three and a half

00:43:29.320 --> 00:43:36.360
years ago and I wanted more flexibility, um, than in the job that I had at the time. Um, I started

00:43:36.360 --> 00:43:42.199
out finding clients. I've mostly done online marketing. Um, I, I offer online courses as well

00:43:42.199 --> 00:43:49.000
as trainings for organizations. Um, and, um, I've tried to basically become a resource for,

00:43:49.080 --> 00:43:52.679
for other folks. So I write a lot of blog posts, really pitched it like newcomers,

00:43:52.679 --> 00:43:57.479
you know, learning about packages to make, um, effective tables or that type of thing.

00:43:57.479 --> 00:44:00.760
And that's really been my most effective strategy to reach out to clients.

00:44:01.320 --> 00:44:06.679
That's great. So I think we're right at time. Um, so I'd love to give a round of applause

00:44:06.679 --> 00:44:14.840
to the panelists.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:19.500
Thank you.

